for those already blocking notifications with something else or make your

It's good, works well. Only two minor comments. 1. When defining a custom 
size, there should be a way to type in numbers with the keyboard. Using 
sliders as the only method for adjusting a high-precision numbers is a UI 
101 level mistake, it's really difficult to set it to an exact value, like 
making it the same height as the status bar for example. 2. There should be 
an option for putting a space between the value and unit. This makes it 
easier to read, and is the universal convention for writing numbers with 
units according to SI standards. (Bytes of course is not an SI unit but 
it's still a good practice to follow ;)

There's no way a simple Network monitor app all of a sudden needs location 
permissions. This used to be the best app of its kind, used it for years. 
But with the new Android Oreo network bandwidth meter I won't be needing to 
worry about it anyways.

Edit 30/6/2018: phone just updated to the latest version of this app (1.0.213), and it asked for permissions to location, contacts, files, etc. Why? What does any of this have to do with network throughput? I granted the permissions so that the update would install, and then immediately went to app settings and removed those permissions, and it still seems to work ok. But having those permissions asked for makes it feel like spyware...  Works well. Only fault I've noticed is that when using the phone as a wireless access point for my laptop, the network monitor doesn't show any throughput when the laptop is uploading or downloading via the tethered phone. Pixel 2 running Android 8.1.

I'm one of those people who wonders what's going on when my stuff is 
online. This app tells me when there is traffic, how much there is, and if 
I set the option for it, which app is doing it. It sits on my screen 
wherever I want, and it just works. It's the best I've ever used... the 
last one I was this happy with was on a DOS machine... so it's been a long 
wait. It won't analyze or inspect packets... but it does tell me when I 
might want to. The developers are responsive and helpful as the features 
demonstrate. I consider it to be a sort of speedometer/odometer for my 
tablet, and as a sort of "engine light". I highly recommend it.
